<br>
From your posts, I reckon you probably do a lot of this already, which is cool =) .. Hell, if you do all of it (and more) then I'd say you're probably well on your way to having a good rep on your server, if you don't have one already (and don't know about it).. But here's some thoughts anyway....<br>
<br>
.  Be known for being a considerate Warrior, one who respects his caster's mana levels. Be seen to quote the rule: If your casters aren't ready, your group ain't ready. Your casters *will* notice this and appreciate it. At the same time, *don't* wait after every pull for sleepy_cleric01 to tell you he's 95m. I usually tell groups when I join them that I pull until the cleric cries for mercy. It gets a laugh, and the group know that a) they'll be getting chain exp, and b) I will stop when told to by the casters.<br>
<br>
. Be known for being a friendly Warrior. Always welcome new arrivals to the group. Have a laugh, have a joke. re: my pull until cleric cries for mercy quote above. Say funny things during the fights. I have two banks of macros - one 'serious' one for raid situations, and one 'joke' one for normal exp grouping. No one likes the exp grind, it's heartless and soul-destroying, and people like to have a joke around to liven things up, otherwise you'll find everyone's falling asleep on their keyboards. Say stuff like 'Taunting a Drolvarg Rager, telling him his momma was a gnoll!', or after a particularly damaging pull, say 'Bringing in a Drachnid Silkmistress, errr .. I damaged her a bit. Sorry, guys.' Don't be a fool, but don't be aloof either. Strong and silent only works in Hollywood movies.<br>
<br>
. Be known for being a courteous Warrior. Don't be one of the jokers that spam /shout and /ooc with pointless streams of d00dsp34k. Don't continually ask where the 'ph4t lewtz' drop. Don't be the first to jump on the corpse when it dies. If your cleric is symbolling you (which he probably doesn't need to if you're killing trash in DL, but anyway) then offer up some gems or whatever for the costs. He may refuse them, but the offer is nice. Maybe he won't, but hey, there's more to life than money, right?<br>
<br>
. Be known for being a professional Warrior. esepecially one that knows how to hold and retain aggro. Taunt intelligently and use melee proximity to your advantage. If there's rogues in the party, make sure you're not pushing the mob back into a wall, that sort of thing. People appreciate that sort of thing. If your ranger's not jolting and pulling aggro, then politely suggest that he do so. Explain to your group that as a Warrior, most of the time you don't take aggro, it has to be given to you by the other melees. Monks FD, Rangers jolt, Rogues evade, etc etc. Be friendly about it, etc etc. It also demonstrates your in-game knowledge and appreciation of other classes skills and abilities. People notice this, too.<br>
<br>
The repuation you're looking for is two-fold. Skill *and* personality. I know Warriors who are respected for their skill and in-game knowledge, but people won't group with them because they're regarded as assholes as well. And vice versa - I know Warrior who are the nicest guys in the world, but don't know the first thing about the Warrior class.<br>
<br>
You want your name to be known, not just as a tank who knows his stuff, but also one who's a nice guy, fun to be around and is always good for a laugh.<br>
<br>
Whilst it may be true that a equipment makes or breaks a Warrior, your actions will make or break your repuation.<br>
<br>
Remember - When people shout LFG, they don't list their equipment. Just their name..... <p>--
